{{Platform |Name=Adventure Vision |Guid=3045-93 |Aliases=Entex Adventure Vision,Entex Electronic Arcade |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/46/1248213-adventurevision.jpg |Deck=The Adventure Vision is a handheld video game console developed by Entex Industries in 1982. |ShortName=AVIS |ReleaseDate=August 1982 |ReleaseDateType=Month |InstallBase=50,000 |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=79.99 |Manufacturer=Companies/Entex }}
==Overview== Released in late 1982 by Entex, the [[Platforms/Adventure_Vision|Adventure Vision]] is actually a handheld console though it is way too big to be used as a proper handheld device. The console is self-contained, and thus no external monitor is needed, and uses game cartridges. As far as the monitor goes, it uses one string of 40 red LEDs and a spinning mirror (just like [[Companies/Nintendo|Nintendo]]'s [[Platforms/Virtual_Boy|Virtual Boy]]) instead of an LCD screen, which leads to a resolution of 150 x 40 pixels and an amount of 15 frames per second. That kind of monitor was a huge drawback, as no other console at the time used that techique. Not to mention that the mirror drew a large amount of power from the batteries, although the AC adapter that is built in solves that. Due to the monitor, only 4 games were released for it.
==Technical Specifications== * '''CPU''': Intel 8048 running @ 733 KHz * '''Sound:''' National Semiconductor COP411L @ 52.6 KHz * '''RAM:''' 64 bytes (8048-internal), and 1K (on main PCB) * '''ROM:''' 1K (8048-internal), 512 bytes (COP411L-internal) and 4K (game cartridge) * '''Input:''' 4 direction joystick * '''Graphics''': 150x40 monochrome pixels, running @ 15 FPS

{{Platform |Name=Amiga CD32 |Guid=3045-39 |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/26/10070-cd32.jpg |Deck=The Amiga CD32 was Commodore's attempt at a gaming console and what turned out to be their swan song. The majority of its library were upgraded Amiga games. |ShortName=CD32 |ReleaseDate=1993-09-17 |InstallBase=125,000 |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=249.99 |Manufacturer=Companies/Commodore }} <div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"10070-cd32.jpg","path":"0\/26\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"scale_medium,scale_super,square_mini,square_medium,square_small,screen_medium,square_avatar,scale_small,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_tiny,scale_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":"Amiga CD32"},"background":[]}' /> The Amiga CD32 was released in September 1993, and it was the first 32-bit cd-rom console to be released in [[Locations/Europe|Europe]] and [[Locations/Canada|Canada]]. Although the plans for releasing it in the US never happened. The Amiga had similar specs as the Amiga 1200 and had the possibility to add mouse, keyboard, etc. It also had a covered expansion slot intended to accomodate a VideoCD playback module. This was eventually utilized by third parties to create other expansion modules that allowed the CD32 to act as a fully capable Amiga computer, first by adding missing ports and later providing for the ability to add a hard drive, memory and upgrade the CPU. The console lasted only for approximately seven months due to component supply issues and therefore it didn't have the sales impact to keep the console alive. However, the console was kept alive in other forms: In the late 1990s to early 2000s, slot machine manufacturer StarGames utilized a stripped down CD32 motherboard in many of their slot machines and in the mid to late 1990s, some vehicle registries in Canada utilized CD32 systems for interactive multimedia testing for drivers license applications. The CD32 also had a unique piece of hardware called the Akiko chip that was added specifically to enable the console to more easily support "Doom clones". It provided acceleration for converting the PC's chunky pixel format (which was better suited to the routines that generated the graphics in Doom-like games) to the Amiga's planar pixel format.
==Technical Specifications==
{| class='wikitable' style='margin:auto;width:100%;' |- | '''Processor'''||Motorola 68EC020 @ 14.32 MHz (NTSC) or 14.18 MHz (PAL) |- | '''RAM'''||2 MB Amiga Chip RAM |- | '''ROM'''||1 MB Kickstart w/ CD32 firmware 1 KB EEPROM for game saves |- | '''Graphics'''||&lt;p&gt;Advanced Graphics Architecture (AGA)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Akiko chip&lt;/p&gt; |- | '''Sound'''||4 x 8-bit PCM channels |- | '''Screen Resolution'''||320x200 to 1280x400i (NSTC) 320x256 to 1280x512i (PAL) |- | ''' Operating System'''||AmigaOS 3.1 |}

{{Platform |Name=Arcadia 2001 |Guid=3045-99 |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/46/187197-arcadia2001.gif |Deck=Arcadia 2001 is an 8-bit console made by Emerson. |ShortName=A2K1 |ReleaseDate=May 1982 |ReleaseDateType=Month |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=99.99 |Manufacturer=Companies/Emerson_Radio_Corporation }}
The Arcadia 2001 is an [[Concepts/8_bit|8-bit]] console made by [[Companies/Emerson_Radio_Corporation|Emerson Radio Corp.]] that took the model of licensing the console to various manufacturers, ending up with over 30 Arcadia clones. Its graphical power is comparable to that of the [[Platforms/Intellivision|Intellivision]] and [[Platforms/Odyssey_2|Odyssey 2]].
==Technical Specifications== * '''Processor:''' Signetics 2650 CPU @ 3.58 MHz * '''RAM:''' 512 bytes * '''ROM:''' None * '''Graphics:''' Signetics 2637 UVI * '''Sound:''' Single Channel "Beeper" + Single Channel "Noise"

{{Platform |Name=Browser |Guid=3045-140 |Aliases=Facebook,World Wide Web,In-Browser,Flash Games,Java Games,HTML5 Games,Chrome web store |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/4231/942780-q20.jpg |Deck=Browser-based games are typically platform-independent pieces of software that run directly in the same application you use to read this web page. |ShortName=BROW |ReleaseDate=1991-08-31 |ReleaseDateType=Month |OnlineSupport=Yes |OriginalPrice=0.00 }} <div id='imageData' data-json='{"infobox":{"file":"942780-q20.jpg","path":"0\/4231\/","mime":"image\/jpeg","sizes":"square_avatar,square_small,scale_small,square_mini,square_tiny,scale_medium,screen_medium,scale_large,scale_avatar,square_medium,scale_super,scale_tiny,screen_kubrick","caption":"Quake Live in FireFox"},"background":[]}' />
==Overview==
===Guidelines for Inclusion=== It benefits a game if it can meet one or more of these criteria. * Games that have been discussed in an editorial capacity * Games that have been developed by designers already included in the Giant Bomb database for their work on other, more traditional platforms. * Games that have cards giving points/money and/or items. * Is legal and not a modification that violates copyright laws. * &lt;p&gt;Please make sure you can supply a firm release date when adding Browser-based games.&lt;/p&gt;

{{Platform |Name=Casio PV-1000 |Guid=3045-149 |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/14/148570/2318191-casio_pv_1000.jpg |Deck=The Casio PV-1000 was released in Japan in 1983. Only 15 games were produced. |ShortName=PV1K |ReleaseDate=October 1983 |ReleaseDateType=Month |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=148.00 |Manufacturer=Companies/Casio_Co_Ltd }}
Produced by [[Companies/Casio_Co_Ltd|Casio]] in October 1983, the PV-1000 cost 14,800¥ at launch and had a Z80A processor and a mere 2kb of RAM (half of which was dedicated to the Character Generator) under the hood. It was released alongside a "[[Platforms/Casio_PV_2000|PV-2000]]" computer system that was compatible with the PV-1000's controllers, but not its games. Ultimately, the system is only notable for its dismal failure: Only 15 titles were ever produced, and legend has it that the system was pulled from shelves after just weeks. As a result, the system is startlingly rare to find. Casio replaced it with two [[Platforms/MSX|MSX]]-based computers that same year, the PV-7 and PV-16, ensuring that it would not be mourned. They would try their hand at consoles again, over a decade later with the [[Platforms/Casio_Loopy|Casio Loopy]].
==Technical Specifications== * '''CPU:''' Zilog Z80A @ 3.579 MHz * '''RAM:''' 2 KB * '''Video Display:''' 256x192; 8 available colours

{{Platform |Name=ColecoVision |Guid=3045-47 |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/26/1270971-colecovision.jpg |Deck=The ColecoVision came out in 1982 and had a successful run as the Atari 5200's competitor until 1984. |ShortName=CVIS |ReleaseDate=August 1982 |ReleaseDateType=Month |InstallBase=2,000,000 |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=179.99 |Manufacturer=Companies/Coleco }}
==Overview== ColecoVision is a video game console made by Coleco Industries. It was released in August of 1982. It was a home system with arcade type games. It also featured the strange ability to play Atari 2600 games, its competitor. About 120 titles were released for the ColecoVision during its lifespan. The ColecoVision came with the game Nintendo's Donkey Kong as a pack-in game and is revered as a near-perfect arcade port. This increased the popularity of the ColecoVision and by the end of 1982 the ColecoVision had sold 500,000 units. Atari's marketing for a short time claimed the 5200 was more powerful, but ColecoVision did much better than the Atari 5200 in sales, and since the 5200 was based on the Atari 400/800 which was 3 years older, this claim didn't appear to hold much truth. Although the ColecoVision, at the time showed great sales and growth, the Atari 2600 still ruled the roost. The growth of the ColecoVision and the huge install base of the Atari 2600 helped start the first true Multi-platform movement in consoles. Activision, Parker Brothers, and several other companies for a short time released some titles on near the same launch day for both consoles. The ColecoVision eventually sold more the one million units by 1983. Outside of the United States, the ColecoVision is known as the CBS ColecoVision as it was distributed by CBS Electronics. The ColecoVision was discontinued in 1984 due to the crash of the video game market in 1983. The ColecoVision had three different expansion peripherals: * '''Expansion Module #1''': This allowed the ColecoVision to play Atari 2600 games which largely expanded the ColecoVision game library. * '''Expansion Module #2:''' This was a driving controller that came with the pack-in game Turbo. It was only compatible with two other games from the ColecoVision library: Destructor and Dukes of Hazzard. * '''Expansion Module #3:''' The ColecoVision's third expansion turned it into a computer called the Coleco Adam. It came with a full keyboard and digital dat pack cassette drives. The primary games of the ColecoVision library were arcade games that Atari had not yet licensed. The most popular of the ColecoVision games were Donkey Kong, Donkey Kong Junior, Carnival, Lady Bug, Mouse Trap, and Zaxxon.
==Technical Specifications==
{| class='wikitable' style='margin:auto;width:100%;' |- | '''Processor'''||NEC Zilog Z80A @ 3.58 MHz |- | '''RAM'''||1 KB (two 1K x 4-bit chips) |- | '''ROM'''||8 KB TMS4764 Mask ROM |- | '''Graphics'''||&lt;p data-right-indent="0" data-left-indent="0"&gt;Texas Instruents TMS99928A Video Display Controller&lt;/p&gt;* 256x192 pixel resolution * 32 sprints on-screen * 16 colors |- | '''Sound'''||&lt;p data-right-indent="0" data-left-indent="0"&gt;Texas Intstuments SN76489A PSG chip&lt;/p&gt;* 3 tone generators * 1 noise generator |- | '''Storage'''||ROM Cartridge (8, 16, 24 or 32 KB capacity) |}

{{Platform |Name=Entex Select-A-Game |Guid=3045-184 |Image=https://www.giantbomb.com/a/uploads/scale_super/0/1992/3195565-entex-selectagame.jpg |Deck=Entex's Select-A-Game is a handheld console that was released in 1981. Only six games were officially released before it was discontinued. |ShortName=ESAG |ReleaseDate=1981 |ReleaseDateType=Year |OnlineSupport=No |OriginalPrice=54.99 |Manufacturer=Companies/Entex }}
==Overview== Select-A-Game was developed by [[Companies/Entex|Entex]], an electronics company based in Compton, [[Locations/California|California]]. The console features a 16 x 7 screen that could produce red or blue lights through a vacuum florescent display. The console itself has no processor. Instead, each game cartridge comes equipped with its own processor.
==Games== Eight games were developed for the Select-A-Game, but only six were officially released. [[Games/Pacman_2|Pacman 2]] became controversial, and rare as a result, because [[Companies/Coleco|Coleco]] sued Entex over its release. At the time, Coleco held exclusive publishing rights to any handheld versions of [[Franchises/Pac_Man|Pac-Man]]. The game was pulled from shelves and is now considered a collector's item. * [[Games/Baseball_4|Baseball 4]] * Basketball 3 * Battleship (not released) * Football 4 * [[Games/Pacman_2|Pacman 2]] * Pinball * [[Games/Space_Invader_2|Space Invader 2]] * Turtles (not released)
